利用niji跑图练的风格lora，除本身画风外。还能提高对男性塑造。推荐权重受大模型影响，可自行尝试

给予访客使用模型的一些建议与回答

（作为一个外行人，虽然没有经历过美术和ai的专业课学习，但我仍然在不断努力学习探索，并与各位大佬交流心得。我对自己在意的事情有着很高的精神洁癖，因此我希望能在自己的一亩三分地里传达正确的ai知识。）

1、LORA

  • 对于动漫角色lora而言，最好的权重便是1。虽然我们能通过改变权重的方式来改善拟合，但改变权重会额外产生一些不好影响。比如：c站动漫角色lora大多数都过拟合，而为了改善这一现象往往会推荐降低权重到0.6/0.8，而这一举动会导致角色失去部分原本的外貌特征

  • 过拟合通俗解释：过分训练导致的lora表现僵化，如人物不听tag话甚至出原本素材的图

2、CKPT

  • clip偏移和unet过拟合都会导致模型不听tag话

  • clip偏移会导致tag识别问题，c站有相当一部分模型存在此问题而不自知，如果你感兴趣，在下面的“其他”里我会给予检查及简单修复的途径

  • unet过拟合也会让模型僵化，不听tag使唤，甚至在无tag的情况下跑出好看的图片，这也是过拟合吐原图的情况

  • 融合类ckpt能够很好的提高模型出图的下限，但融合模型对于tag的权重是很乱的，因此会各具“特色”，同样，基于此类模型训练的lora很难在其他模型上适用

3、VAE

  • CKPT自身就有一个VAE，外挂VAE不是用于额外的增加，而是用于替换

  • VAE只是最直观的是饱和度变化，这并非VAE功能的全部，就对于跑图而言还会改变构图、细节等等

4、其他

  • 模型占内存大的不一定好，很多模型内有一堆无用数据，下载完全浪费流量内存

  • 示例图的好坏不能确定模型质量，除了基于作者本身审美外，你无法确定他用了多少模型、插件的辅助，你也无法确定他文生图跑了几次、图生图跑了几次

  • 下载量与点赞也不能确定模型质量，点赞量基于下载量，而下载量会和作者名气、封面图片受众、模型角色人气、模型画风受众、模型类型受众等等相关

  • 模型并非版本最新为最好，很多时候是基于某一版本的不同方向的调整。甚至有部分作者为了通过更新的推送而蹭到更多的下载量而恶意刷更新，实际使用下来模型的质量不过是在原地迂回踏步

  • 其他更为专业详细的知识请看万象熔炉 | Anything V5/Ink的简介部分，关于clip偏移的检验修复的扩展链接在此文档前段部分中

items.name: The King in Yellow (Hastur) - Character LoRA
items.description:
"And now, far away, over leagues of tossing cloud-waves, I saw the moon dripping with spray; and beyond, the towers of Carcosa rose behind the moon. Death and the awful abode of lost souls, whither my weakness long ago had sent him, had changed him for every other eye but mine. And now I heard his voice, rising, swelling, thundering through the flaring light, and as I fell, the radiance increasing, increasing, poured over me in waves of flame. Then I sank into the depths, and I heard the King in Yellow whispering to my soul:

'It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God!'"
- Robert W. Chambers, In the Court of the Dragon

Hello folks,

I'm continuing my series of Lovecraftian creatures and characters with probably the second most iconic villain of the Necronomicon: Hastur. There a few other Hastur models out there (konyconi's and passer's), but it looks like we have a different training dataset and overall approach to the character. My interpretation of the King in Yellow is closer to the original Chambers story, inspired by John Scott Tynes's "Carcosa cycle," as opposed to the Call of Cthulhu /August Derleth interpretation. Still, the model is quite flexible, and you should be able to conjure the King in Yellow from your own dreams.

Notes:

  • Trained on Clip Skip 1. That doesn't mean it won't work on Clip Skip 2 models (it works okay), just that I'm not testing it extensively on Clip Skip 2 models.

  • Then model is flexible, so depending on your prompts you can go for a masked visage or one shrouded in darkness.

  • In general, weights of 0.8-1.0 seem good.

  • Tentacles are a bit inconsistent. It's tough to get the tentacle legs seen in Call of Cthulhu interpretations of the character. I have some ideas to improve on that for future versions.

  • By the way, have you seen the yellow sign?

This time the LoRA was trained using the CyberRealistic model rather than Avalon TruVision as before.

District 9 is a 2009 science fiction action film directed by Neill Blomkamp in his feature film debut, written by Blomkamp and Terri Tatchell, and produced by Peter Jackson and Carolynne Cunningham. It is a co-production of New Zealand, the United States, and South Africa. The film stars Sharlto Copley, Jason Cope, and David James, and was adapted from Blomkamp's 2006 short film Alive in Joburg.

The film is partially presented in a found footage format by featuring fictional interviews, news footage, and video from surveillance cameras. The story, which explores themes of humanity, xenophobia and social segregation, begins in an alternate 1982, when an alien spaceship appears over Johannesburg, South Africa. When a population of sick and malnourished insectoid aliens is discovered on the ship, the South African government confines them to an internment camp called District 9. Twenty years later, during the government's relocation of the aliens to another camp, one of the confined aliens named Christopher Johnson, who is about to try to escape from Earth with his son and return home, crosses paths with a bureaucrat named Wikus van de Merwe leading the relocation. The title and premise of District 9 were inspired by events in Cape Town's District Six, during the apartheid era.

A viral marketing campaign for the film began in 2008 at San Diego Comic-Con, while the theatrical trailer debuted in July 2009. District 9 was released by TriStar Pictures on 14 August 2009, in North America and became a financial success, earning over $210 million at the box office. It also received acclaim from critics, with some calling it one of the best science fiction films of the 2000s, and garnered numerous awards and nominations, including four Academy Award nominations for Best Picture, Best Adapted Screenplay, Best Visual Effects, and Best Film Editing.

=- The models -================================================================

* Early experiments - These models have very bad tagging and dont have a way to control what they generate, so they are best used just as a style or in combinations with other LoRAs, otherwise you will be rolling a dice on what kind of robot you get.

AB_robot - Very first test, trained on NAI but capable of generating realistic looking stuff too, at least until you use a few more tags and than it locks you into purely drawn styles.

AB_robot_MRG - This one was trained on one of my custom model merges of SD1.5 and several anime models, this one can generate some pretty hot robot babes and can give pretty consistent results.

AB_robot_SD15 - This one was trained on SD1.5 and seems a bit bland but results are consistent.

AB_robot_SDNAI60-final - This one was trained on my custom merge of SD1.5 and NAI and can do realistic designs and very nice looking close up of metallic robot heads.

AB_robot-naisd60-morefinal - This one is fire, it was also trained on my custom SDNAI merge and is capable of doing even cooler looking upper body and head stuff.

* Final models - These had a lot more training material and use a system of tags that allow you to have more control over how your robot will look like, a full list of all the tags and everything is down bellow. These models will work best with AOM2 and do not need any triggers to function.

GR-SDNAI6-DIM32-A16-v1 - This was a test run to see if adding the extra training data along with several days spent tagging it all paid off. main problem with it is the images it generate are too dark due to most of my training images being very dark, also too many images of the call of duty robot also messed with it, generating upper body parts of it everything. But included this because it can generate some cool stuff the the models bellow cant.

GR-NAI-DIM32-A16 - This one is the final final model, it was trained on NAI but is more suitable for more realistic stuff strangely enough, also seems to be a lot better at recreating the material it was trained on.

GR-SD-DIM32-A16 - This one is another final model of the final model. It was trained on SD1.5 but is completely incompatible with SD1.5 itself and is much better suited for stylistic designs using anime models as base.

I have no idea how to add multiple versions so the remaining 2 models are in the trianing data download zip

The robot girl LoRAa by PillowWaifu

These dont requiore any specific samplers or CFG or any other settings to work (other than maybe clip skip 2 on some models) and will work pretty well with any model (that i tried at least), even AOM2 and mixes really well with other LoRAs.

- MB_robot-NAI-v1 - This one was my first attempt and goofed things up a little with the tags and included unnecessary triggers, which makes the style a bit of a blend of everything it was trained on and harder to control and theres a built in PVC effect that comes out without being prompted for(does it the most on AOM2), but is still pretty usable. You can tone down the PVC with negative tags, if you do it just a little, you will get a really nice blend of art and realism, experiment with it to see what you can come up with. As a side effect to bad tagging, its easier to use just the visual style of this LoRA without any of the robot stuff.

- Frea-NAI - This one is kind of a rush job, it was originally ment to do the desktop army's Frea characters but its badly tagged, trained under the wrong settings and is kinda fried and lol, but if you tone it down by half, you can still use it to do some pretty cool mecha musume stuff and use the MB_robot-NAI-v2 instead to generate Freas.

- MB_robot-NAI-v2 - This one has much better tagging, no unnecessary triggers (PVC wont happen unless you prompt for it) is easier to control and just overall looks a lot better if you wanna make robot girls. But for some reason its harder to just use its style alone without the robot stuff and the PVC effect is not as good as in MB_robot-NAI-v1, also the androids it generates dont look as good as v1 either, so dont write v1 off just yet cause it will be useful too.

- Some notable tags -

MB_robot - Global trigger used in MB_robot-NAI-v1.

robot, robot girl - More global triggers.

frea - Desktop army's Frea characters.

frea red - To trigger the red one specifically, doesnt fully work cause is didnt tag everything properly.

frea green - Same as above.

pvc, figure - PVC anime figure style.

medabots, medabot - Medabot style (looks a bit bad in )

mecha musume - Mecha musume !

mechanization - Turning non robot characters into robots.

humanoid robot, android, mecha - The type of robot you are going for.

mobile suit - This one had only 1 pic to train on and is mostly just a placeholder for when i make a v3 of this model that will have more material of this kind, but this tag still kinda works if you combine it the mecha tag and a some other tags.

Check the tags lists included in each folder to see the rest of the tags.
